edu.caltech.sbw
Class Module

java.lang.Object
  |
  +--edu.caltech.sbw.Module
public class Module
extends java.lang.Object

Objects of this class represent an instance of a module. They act as client-side proxies for running modules; a Module class object stands for an actual module, meaning the corresponding application, that is running on the user's computer or perhaps another computer. Having a reference to a Module object in a program implies that the SBW Broker has started up at least one instance of the corresponding real module. (This is in contrast to having an instance of a ModuleDescriptor object, which describes a module but does not imply that an instance of the module is necessarily running.) Actions taken on the proxy objects themselves, such as destroying a Module object, has no effect on the real module instance.

Module Attributes

A Module has several possible attributes: a unique name (where uniqueness is considered in the context of a session managed by a specific SBW Broker), a display name, a management type (see section below), a help string, and a set of services. A Module object contains zero or more Service objects which represent the services implemented by the module. These services can be listed or searched by name and category using the three methods getServices(), findServicesByCategory(java.lang.String) and findServiceByName(java.lang.String).

It is possible for a module to connect to an SBW Broker without advertising the availability of any services and without registering itself with a name and other attributes. In that case, the values of some attributes of a Module proxy object may be empty.

Module Management Types

Depending on the kind of services a module implements and the style of use intended, it may be more suitable to have multiple copies (instances) of a module running, or to have only one instance running. Modules that do not keep state information are often best implemented as having only one copy running in an SBW system. For example, a module that performs data conversion operations could run as a unique instance in an SBW system, avoiding the resource usage that would result if a fresh copy were started every time that a client module requested its services.

SBW allows a module developer to designate the type of management that SBW should assume for a module. The type is indicated by a flag to the constructors for the ModuleImpl class. A client holding a reference to a Module object can find out the management type of that module by obtaining a ModuleDescriptor object using the method getDescriptor() and then using ModuleDescriptor.getManagementType() on the result.

findServiceByName

public Service findServiceByName(java.lang.String serviceName)
                          throws SBWCommunicationException
Returns a Service object representing the service with the given name implemented by this module instance. Returns null if such a service doesn't exist on the module. The name matching performed is case-sensitive and exact, with the modification that any leading and trailing whitespace in the argument serviceName are first removed before attempting the match.

findServicesByCategory

Returns an array of Service objects corresponding to all the services in the given category implemented by this module instance. Returns an empty array if there is no service with a category that matches the parameter category. The name matching performed is case-sensitive and exact, with the modification that any leading and trailing whitespace in category are first removed before attempting the match.

equals

public boolean equals(java.lang.Object other)
Indicates whether some other object is "equal to" this one. This method implements equality for Module objects, overriding the method of the same name on the basic Java Object class. If the given object is a Module object and its module instance identifier is equal to this module's, then this method returns true, else it returns false. This equivalence means that the two module proxy objects refer to the same running instance of a module.

Overrides:
equals in class java.lang.Object
Parameters:
other - the object with which to compare this one.
Returns:
true if the argument is a Module object that refers to the same module as this object, false otherwise.

hashCode

public int hashCode()
Returns a hash code value for this object. This overrides the method of the same name on the basic Java Object class.

From the definition of Object.hashCode(), the general contract of hashCode() is:

  • Whenever it is invoked on the same object more than once during an execution of a Java application, the hashCode() method must consistently return the same integer, provided no information used in equals(java.lang.Object) comparisons on the object is modified. This integer need not remain consistent from one execution of an application to another execution of the same application.
  • If two objects are equal according to the equals(Object) method, then calling the hashCode() method on each of the two objects must produce the same integer result.
  • It is not required that if two objects are unequal according to the Object.equals(java.lang.Object) method, then calling the hashCode() method on each of the two objects must produce distinct integer results. However, the programmer should be aware that producing distinct integer results for unequal objects may improve the performance of hashtables.

hashCode in class java.lang.Object
